article.description: Behind Nykesha Sales' 28 points, the Connecticut Sun beat the Charlotte Sting 81-67 Wednesday night to take sole possession of first place in the Eastern Conference.
article.headline: Sales' 28 points lead Connecticut charge
article.linkText: Sun put down Sting, take East's top spot
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The Connecticut Sun clinched a playoff
spot for the second straight season behind Nykesha Sales'
season-high 28 points in an 81-67 win over the Charlotte Sting on
Wednesday night.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 19 points and 10 rebounds for the
Sun (17-15), who moved into sole possession of first place in the
tightly bunched Eastern Conference.

Charlotte and Washington are tied for second place, one game
back.

"We're in the playoffs now, but we want to finish first in the
conference to get home-court advantage," Sales said. "Before the
(Olympic) break we weren't playing that well, and now it's coming
together."

Tammy Sutton-Brown tied a career high with 22 points, and
Allison Feaster and Tynesha Lewis added 15 apiece for the Sting,
who had their three-game winning streak snapped.

The Sun, who hold the tiebreaker edge over every other team in
the East, shot 53 percent in their fourth straight win. Connecticut
owns the best conference record (13-5).

Katie Douglas opened the second half with a 3-pointer, igniting
a 7-0 run that gave Connecticut a 41-32 lead with 18:13 left. The
Sun added to the lead behind Sales, who finished three shy of her
career-high on 12-of-20 shooting.

Sales had consecutive 3-pointers and a layup to give the Sun a
63-45 lead with 10:10 left.

Sales finished 3-of-6 from behind the arc for the Sun, who made
17-of-29 field goals in the second half.

"She just took over," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "I could
tell this morning that she had a pretty good shooting rhythm. She
took her time and stepped into almost every shot she took."

Charlotte finishes the season on the road against San Antonio
and Detroit. The top four teams in each conference make the
playoffs.

"If anybody on this team wants to make the playoffs, on Friday
night (at San Antonio) there is a playoff spot on the line," Sting
guard Dawn Staley said. "I know that whoever steps out on the
court with me is going to understand they have to take it a little
more seriously and have more energy."

Connecticut held a 46-24 advantage in the paint and outrebounded
the Sting, 31-18.

Sutton-Brown had only five rebounds and struggled defensively in
the paint against McWilliams-Franklin, who recorded her sixth
double-double on 7-of-13 shooting.

"Rebounding is all about heart and that has to be a focal
point," Sutton-Brown said. "If we don't do it now we don't
deserve the playoffs."
